
[1]warmth

   WARMNESS, WARMTH, n.

   1. Gentle heat; as the warmth of the blood.

   2. Zeal; ardor; fervor; as the warmth of love or of piety.

   3. Earnestness; eagerness. The cause of the Greeks has been espoused
   with warmth by all parties in free countries.

   4. Excitement; animation; as the warmth of passion. The preacher
   declaimed with great warmth against the vices of the age.

   5. Fancifulness; enthusiasm; as the warmth of head.

   6. In painting, the fiery effect given to a red color by a small
   addition of yellow.
